    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i think i get the coin thing. but you mentioned it's \"bizarre\" or unlike regular correlations. some people call it \"spooky action at a distance,\" right? why exactly is that part considered so weird or spooky for scientists? like what's the actual problem with it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Spooky action at a distance,\" as Einstein famously called it, is weird because it seems to violate our everyday understanding of how information should travel. With regular correlations, like knowing two socks match, the properties were *already* set when they were separated. In entanglement, the particles don't have a definite state—like heads or tails—until one is measured. It's as if the measurement on one particle *forces* the other particle, light-years away, to instantly decide its state. That instantaneous coordination is the spooky part!",
