    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if they dont have a set state until you look at them, how do they actually know what the other one is doing? is there like some kind of hidden force or something connecting them that we just havent found yet?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's the million-dollar question, and it's what keeps physicists up at night, which is precisely why it's so fascinating! The prevailing view, supported by tons of experimental evidence, is that there isn't some little, hidden messenger particle zipping between them—no secret, tiny 'information-carrying' wormhole that we haven't found yet. The idea of \"hidden variables,\" which would be like a secret instruction manual tucked inside each particle telling it what to be, has been largely ruled out by tests like Bell's inequalities.\n\nIt's less like they are *telling* each other, and more like they are fundamentally *one system* described by a single quantum state, even when separated. Think of it like a pair of specialized, interconnected, highly volatile magical bombs that were forged together in a single, shared crucible. When you trigger one, the other reacts instantly because they are part of the same initial, unified creation. This isn't like two separate, pre-programmed bombs; it's more like they are two aspects of a single, weirdly connected entity.",
